'''''Star Saga One: Beyond the Boundary''''' is the first game in the ''[[Star Saga]]'' series.

==Gameplay==
<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Star Saga One.jpg|thumb|left|Oversized ''Star Saga: One'' box]] -->
'''''Star Saga: One - Beyond The Boundary''''', released in 1988, was the first in a short-lived series of [[science fiction]] [[adventure game|adventure]]/[[role-playing game|role-playing]] games by [[Masterplay Publishing]]. Loosely based on the [[Rekon]] pen & paper role-playing system,<ref name="gamasutra">{{Citation | url=http://www.gamasutra.com/features/20070223b/barton_pfv.htm | title=The History of Computer Role-Playing Games Part 2: The Golden Age(1985–1993) | last=Barton | first=Matt | publisher=[[Gamasutra]] | date=2007-02-23}}</ref> the game series was designed by [[Andrew C. Greenberg]] (co-creator of ''[[Wizardry]]''), Rick Dutton, Walter Freitag, and Michael Massimilla.<ref name="cgw1">{{Citation | last=Kritzen | first=William | title=The Stars... My Destiny | magazine=[[Computer Gaming World]] | volume=50 | pages=39–40 | date=August 1988 | url=https://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/issues/cgw_50.pdf }}</ref>  In this first title, players leave their homeworlds setting out to explore the vast unknowns of space.{{Citation needed|date=November 2020}}

The game includes 13 manuals, 6 character booklets, 2 maps, and a reference guide. <ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|date=December 19, 1988|title=SEASON'S NEW COMPUTER GAMES UNDERGO A TEEN-AGER'S SCRUTINY|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/business/1988/12/19/seasons-new-computer-games-undergo-a-teen-agers-scrutiny/e05f4aee-fa01-4d2c-9192-32c2d1801ace/|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref>

==Reception==
''Star Saga'' was hailed as being completely new and different from games which came before. The ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' review of the first title summarizes this sentiment as "''Star Saga: One - Beyond the Boundary'' is probably the most unique and well-written role-playing experience yet to appear in a computer game". The same reviewer noted that it was easy to lose track of time playing "just one more turn" due to the deep experiences provided by the game.<ref name="cgw1" /> In 1989 the magazine gave ''Star Saga One'' a Special Award for Literary Achievement.<ref name="CGW2">{{citation | date = October 1989 | magazine = [[Computer Gaming World]] | title = Game of the Year Awards | pages = 8}}</ref> ''[[Compute!]]'' was less favorable, describing the game as "far more a social event than a computer game". The magazine stated that "it's lackluster without interaction" with other players, and described the user interface as "almost crude by today's standards".<ref name="keiser198808">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1988-08-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_099_1988_Aug#page/n61/mode/2up | title=Star Saga: One—Beyond the Boundary | work=Compute! | date=August 1988 | accessdate=10 November 2013 | author=Keiser, Gregg | pages=60}}</ref> ''Star Saga One: Beyond the Boundary'' was reviewed in 1989 in ''[[Dragon (magazine)|Dragon]]'' #142 by Hartley, Patricia, and Kirk Lesser in "The Role of Computers" column. The reviewers gave the game 3{{frac|1|2}} out of 5 stars.<ref name="Dragon142">{{Citation
